Domestic versus export-led agricultural transformation: Evidence from Ugandaâ€™s
 dairy value chain 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Driven by increased demand from both local and export markets and facilitated
 by far-reaching liberalization and privatization policies, the dairy sub-sector
 in Uganda has undergone significant changes in the last few decades.
 With a comparative advantage in milk production, the southwest of Uganda
 has started to attract considerable Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) in
 processing capacity, mainly targeting the export market.
 At the same time, other milk producing areas such as the central region
 have stepped in to cater for the local market, particularly urban consumers
 in Kampala and other secondary towns.
 We exploit this evolution of the value chain at two speeds to document
 trends in key technological and institutional innovations that both result
 from the emergence of export-led dairy value chains and drive further upgrading.
 Furthermore, as most processors are to some extent involved in export,
 we also correlate these innovations to the level of integration into formal
 value chains as a robustness check.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dairy value chain in Uganda has undergone substantial changes in the
 last few decades.
 These changes were driven by a variety of factors.
 On the demand side, consumption of milk has been on the rise.
 As regional poverty has decreased dramatically, higher incomes resulted
 in rapidly increasing consumption of dairy products, which are known to
 be highly income elastic 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "COLEN2018116,10.1093/jn/133.11.3907S"

\end_inset

.
 Especially in cities, consumers are confronted with an increasing availability
 of various dairy products such as milk, yogurt and ice cream in both informal
 shops and emerging supermarkets, and consumers become increasingly aware
 of the health benefits of dairy products 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ruel2017urbanization,francesconi2010evolution"

\end_inset

.
 But not only local demand for dairy products has increased.
 The dairy sub-sector has also become an important export sector for Uganda.
 On the supply side, the government's liberalization push in the late nineties
 and the eventual privatization of the state parastatal led to a gradual
 increase in competition between processors.
 But the most important supply push is probably the influx of Foreign Direct
 Investment (FDI) in processing capacity geared towards the export market
 from 2014 onward.
 These demand and supply drivers led to a significant transformation of
 the dairy value chain.
 In this paper, we document some of the endogenous innovations that simultaneous
ly occurred at different levels within the chain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interestingly, due to a combination of agglomeration effects and a comparative
 advantage in milk production, the influx of foreign direct investment concentra
ted almost exclusively in the so-called southwestern milk shed, located
 around the town of Mbarara.
 As a result, this area has become tightly integrated in a global export-led
 value chain: in the course of only a few years, the value chain has changed
 dramatically, with large processors sourcing raw milk from farmers, often
 organized in cooperatives, converting raw milk into complex products with
 a long shelf life, such as Ultra High Temperature (UHT) treated milk, mostly
 for export.
 At the same time, a nearby area similar in agro-ecological conditions and
 with similar aggregate production levels, has taken over milk production
 for the local market.
 This area, referred to as the central milk shed, has become the main supplier
 for dairy products in the capital city, Kampala.
 This bifurcation allows us to explore differences between export market-led
 value chain transformation and domestic market-led dynamics.
 At the same time, even in the central milk shed, some farmers reported
 producing for processors that are also engaged in export.
 We therefore also construct and indicator of integration into export-led
 value chains based on links between producers, traders and consumers to
 triangulate our findings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our study mainly relies on primary data, supplemented with data from secondary
 sources.
 The primary data was collected at different nodes in the value chain and
 is used to first describe the structure of the value chain.
 Upstream, we interviewed cattle farmers that produce milk, most of it for
 the market.
 These farmers generally sell raw milk at the farm gate to traders, the
 second category of actors we collected data from.
 However, in the central milk shed, important amounts of milk are also directly
 sold to neighbours, whereas in the southwest, a significant number of farmers
 also sell directly to milk collection centers, often because they are members
 of the cooperative that runs the center.
 Traders and transporters in turn, ship this unprocessed milk to milk collection
 centers, the third category of actors we interviewed.
 In the southwestern milk shed traders also deliver relatively important
 quantities to milk shops.
 Another important actor in the dairy value chain is the processor, who
 sources milk mostly from milk collection centers.
 However, in the central region, milk collection centers also often double
 as shops where neighbours can come and purchase milk.
 Throughout the value chain, volumes of milk in the southwestern milk shed
 are twice as large as volumes in the central milk shed.
 We collected primary data on 1,600 producers, 700 small traders, and 100
 milk collection centers.
 We also collected qualitative data from two processors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We then provide a descriptive analysis of the behaviour of the different
 value chain actors.
 We find significant quantities of milk are marketed.
 In the central milk shed, milk is often sold to neighbours in small quantities.
 Milk fetches relatively high prices on the informal market.
 Farmers sell to traders or use transporters with whom they have an important
 trust relationship.
 Traders visit farmers daily and payments happen weekly or even monthly.
 Farmers that work with one and the same transporter who provides a service
 for a fee seems particularly important in the southwestern milk shed.
 Cooperatives not only seem important for quality control, the often also
 facilitate access to veterinary services.
 All value chain actors struggle with seasonality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we consider innovations that simultaneously occurred at different
 levels within the chain.
 We find some evidence that technology adoption is correlated with being
 integrated in global value chains.
 In the southwestern milk shed, almost 87 percent of animals are of an improved
 breed.
 The central milk shed, half of the cows are still local varieties.
 We also see correlations with milk sanitation: Throughout the dairy value
 chain, custom milk containers are becoming the norm in the export led milk
 shed.
 There are also innovations in terms of how parts of the chain is organized:
 in the export oriented milk shed, proportionally more producers report
 that they are a member of a dairy cooperative.
 Also at the level of the milk collection centers, we also see that cooperatives
 are more prevalent in the southwest.
 We also provide a more in-depth analysis of these innovations and its relation
 to inclusion in export-led value chains using regression analysis and matching
 estimators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our study contributes to the literature in various ways.
 First, most existing studies on value chains in developing countries analyze
 either export-chains 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "maertens2009trade,maertens2009horticulture,minten2009global"

\end_inset

 or domestic chains 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "minten2016feeding,JANSSEN2019327"

\end_inset

.
 This makes it difficult to draw conclusions since one often has to compare
 too many different variables.
 Here we have a case where both export and domestic consumption are an important
 outlet for the same commodity and in the same country.
 This allows us to better capture the importance of the type of value chain
 (export-led versus local) for the innovations we consider.
 Second, with almost 700 small traders interviewed, our study provides evidence
 on the behavior of a group of value chain actors that are hard to capture
 and poorly understood 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "sitko2014exploitative"

\end_inset

.
 Third, while there is a substantial gray literature on dairy value chains
 in Uganda, most of these rely on qualitative data and are limited in terms
 of representatives.
 Our study thus provides an important contribution to understanding the
 dairy sub-sector in Uganda.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of this article is organized as follows.
 The next section uses secondary data to highlight the drivers behind the
 transformation of diary sub-sctor.
 We point out potential demand side drivers and explain how policy reforms
 created an enabling environment that attracted considerable foreign direct
 investment.
 We then present the primary data that was collected at different nodes
 in the value chain in the central and the southwestern milk shed.
 The data is also combined to visualize how raw milk flows through the value
 chain.
 Next, we provide descriptive statistics on key behaviour of the actors
 in the value chain, separately for the two milk sheds.
 For instance, we look at production and market participation of farmers,
 document trader marketing patterns, describe milk collection center operations,
 and processing capacity and export value.
 We then identify a range of innovations that are observed within the chain
 and document how they differ between export-led value chains and domestic-led
 value chains.
 First, this is done by simply describing differences by milk shed.
 Next, a different indicator of integration in global value chains is used
 and a more formal analysis is presented.
 A final section concludes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Drivers of dairy value chain transformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dairy sub-sector in Uganda has grown substantially.
 According to the Uganda Dairy Development Authority, annual milk production
 has increased from 1.4 billion litres of milk in 2006 to 2.2 billion litres
 in 2017/2018.
 The expansion of the sub-sector is driven by an increase in demand, both
 from within Uganda as well as from abroad.
 At the same time, pro-market policy reforms encouraged investment in the
 sub-sector.
\end_layout

