\begin_layout Standard
The previous section explores how key innovations within the dairy value
 chain differs between export led and local value chains by simply comparing
 the southwestern milk shed to the central milk shed.
 However, it may be that in the central milk shed, some actors are also
 integrated in an export led value chain.
 For instance, many farmers from the central region supply Brookside in
 Kampala, which exports substantial parts to Kenya.
 Also, Jesa Dairy Ltd in Wakiso procures most of its milk from the central
 shed.
 According to DDA statistics, Jesa also exports considerable amounts of
 milk.
 At the same time, not all actors located in the southwest produce for the
 export market.
 But simply assuming all actors in the southwest are engaged in dairy export
 and all actors in the central region produce for local markets, differences
 between export-led and local value chains may be attenuated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we construct a more fine grained indicator of participation
 in export-led value chains than simply considering milk shed.
 We do this for two actor in the value chain: farmers and traders.
 For farmers, we create an indicator of integration within the export-led
 dairy value chain that is true if the farmer delivered milk to a milk collectio
n center every day during the week before the survey.
 This could either be deliveries made directly, or indirectly through a
 trader or a transporter.
 Using this definition, we find that half of the farmers in our sample are
 integrated into export-led value chains.
 As expected, there is a clear difference between the sheds: in the central
 region, only about 40 percent is part of an export-led value chain.
 In the southwest, this is almost three quarters of the farmers that were
 interviewed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the trader or transporter, we create an indicator of integration within
 the export-led dairy value chain that is true if the trader or transporter
 reports delivering exclusively to an mcc or directly to the processor.
 According to this definition, about 43 percent of traders are integrated
 into export led value chains.
 As for traders, there is a difference between the sheds, with about 38
 percent of farmers integrated in export-led chains in the cental region,
 while this is 62 percent in the southwestern region.
 
