\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a result of increased demand for dairy products, both locally and from
 abroad, and facilitated by privatization and liberalization, the dairy
 sub-sector in Uganda has transformed substantially.
 Using data collected from farmers, traders, milk collection centers and
 processors, we highlight some of the differences and similarities between
 the central milk shed that caters for the local market and the southwestern
 milk shed that supplies the processors that produce for the export market.
 We also explore patterns in key innovations that are both a cause and consequen
ce of transforming value chains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find seasonality to be a defining feature of dairy farming in Uganda.
 During the rainy season, almost twice as much milk is produced than during
 the dry season.
 This seasonality cuts across the entire value chain.
 In the dry season in the central milk shed, transporters make trips with
 milk cans that are only half full, while in the southern milk shed during
 the rainy season, traders make more than 2.5 trips.
 At the level of milk collection centers, there is considerable under-use
 of this capacity in the dry season, especially in the central milk shed,
 where tanks are on average only 30 percent full.
 Processors complain they can not source sufficient milk, yet they keep
 increasing capacity.
 Prices are relatively high in both sheds during the dry season.
 In rainy season, prices decrease substantially, especially in the southwestern
 milk shed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second important finding that emerges from this study is that increased
 specialization and a reduction in the number of smallholder traders does
 not necessarily mean farmers profit less from diary value chains.
 Indeed, we find that in modern value chains, transporters are less likely
 to engage in price fixing than in informal market where traders work for
 their own account.
 Apparently, prices are determined as a competitive process at the processor
 level, closely tracking the international milk price.
 Actors upstream seem to follow this price, and in the context of frequent
 transactions and a commodity where quality is important, a stable trading
 relationship seems important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, while for other commodities, prices when sold to neigbours are low,
 this is not the case for milk.
 In fact, we find that in the central region, farmers get the best prices
 when they sell directly to fellow villagers.
 This illustrates the importance of the local milk market.
 However, the existence of a local market for which there are less quality
 requirements may hamper (further) development of the dairy value chain.
 For instance, processors may be reluctant to invest in processors (eg.
 by organizing training, providing credit or inputs), if there is a high
 likelihood that the farmer will sell the milk in the local market instead
 of to the processor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "swinnen2015quality"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We further establish that technology adoption is correlated with being integrate
d in global value chains.
 In the southwestern milk shed, almost 87 percent of animals are of an improved
 breed.
 The central milk shed, half of the cows are still local varieties.
 We also see correlations with milk sanitation: Throughout the dairy value
 chain, custom milk containers are becoming the norm in the export led milk
 shed.
 There are also innovations in terms of how parts of the chain is organized:
 in the export oriented milk shed, proportionally more producers report
 that they are a member of a dairy cooperative.
 Also at the level of the milk collection centers, we also see that cooperatives
 are more prevalent in the southwest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though we try to reduce bias due to selection inherent to observational
 data by conditioning on a range of observables using regression and propensity
 score matching, it should be stressed that the dairy value chain innovations
 we consider in this study are endogenous: innovations happen in response
 to transforming value chains while at the same time, these same innovations
 lead to a transformation of the value chain.
 Therefore, our results can not be interpreted as the causal effect of export-le
d value chains on technology adoption, sanitation, or aspects of industrial
 organization such as cooperative membership and specialization.
 
\end_layout

